The paper deals with information theory and its applications to lossy compression and wiretap channels. The concepts of resolvability and approximation of output distributions are central to the paper, which are typically studied in the context of information theory and its subfields such as coding theory, communication theory, and cryptography. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.IT (Information Theory). The paper also involves probabilistic analysis and optimization, which are relevant to sub-categories such as cs.ITP (Information Theory and Probability) and cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper's applications to lossy compression and wiretap channels suggest sub-categories such as cs.SI (Sound and Image Processing) and cs.CC (Computational Complexity).
